Lex Numae. . . si quis hominem liberum rnorti duit, paricida est0,’ Festus; cf. Cic. pro Cluent. 11, Livy 40. 24. Quinctil. inst. 8. 6. 35. The lex Pompeia confined the term to the killing of ascendants, husbands, wives, consobrini, stepfathers and stepmothers, fathers· and mothersinlaw, patrons and descendants, except the killing of a son by his father, Dig. 48. 9. r. Hadrian sentenced a man who killed his son to deportatio, Dig. ib. 5, but this was not included under parricide till the time of Constantine, p. 117 supr.
